Barack Obama receives the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US President
American President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize here as the fourth US President in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma and the medal and a cheque of 1.4 million dollars for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among the peoples.
The head of the White House will arrive tomorrow along with his wife Michelle in the Northwegian metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he pays a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organisations.
The presidential couple then planned a meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja of Norway.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony at which Obama accepts the prestigious prize.
He is the fourth President of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already stated that Obama will talk about the war on Afghanistan when the price is taken over.
The President does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he will accept the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
A few days ago, he intensified the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forgets to highlight.
At the ceremony Obama also received the Golmedaille, the diploma and the cheque for ten million Swedish kroner (about 24 million Czech kroner).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, attended by the Prime Minister and 250 invited guests in addition to Norway's King and Queen.
Obama was very reserved from the beginning to the price.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not quite deserve the price.
He also repeated several times that it was not just the price for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as he.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this was "call to action" for him.
