The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice that characterizes it melts with alarming speed and takes life with it that nowhere else can survive.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have recently entered open water, with diplomats, lawyers and now authors in their keel water.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On Thin Ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice") a natural history of the icon of the north, the polar bear.
Experienced in the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who have proved themselves in hunting the polar bear.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old ensign to the sea, who only fought with the rifle butt of his musket, is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears at a performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have one millionth of the life of a wild animal. The climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore became completely green from the algae that grow in the hollow hairs of its fur.
