Ellis refers to the reports of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the shooting continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and snow-mobile Inuit use powerful assault rifles to hunt down their prey.
Ironically, the ice will remain the longest in the waters in the north of these two hunting nations.
In his new book "After the Ice", Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine "New Scientist", offers a clear and disturbing description of Arctic science and a gripping insight into how the future could develop.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of the changes.
However, this is not due to a lack of explanations.
The pioneer journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and early 20th century for the first time suggested the whirling of the pack ice.
Undersea boats in the Cold War the shifting ridges during the descent.
A useful addition are satellite measurements and the large-scale application of measuring probes on icebergs, but much is still achieved by intrepid people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the strange, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice formed by saltwater troughs compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopic wonders in the ice, all are threatened by the summer ice once passes, which is expected between 2013 and 2050.
