Marines were among the 6,000 who laid wreaths in Arlington
The Chief Private De'Angello Robinson traveled by bus for seven hours to lay a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other marine infantrymen who took the trip from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they stepped.
In a few months, from wherever we're brought back, we could be, Robinson said about the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I'd wish someone would do the same for me, so I'm trying to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to place wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and some others decided to decorate several hundred graves at the Arlington cemetery.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who undertake this journey every year, stop in various cities along the way to perform events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across Amerika (Kräze all over America), which has also extended the event to other countries.
This year, volunteers placed more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves at the Arlington Cemetery, in areas at the Pentagon, at graves at the Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the Memorial to United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 for the purchase and transport of wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way to return something to those who made sacrifices.
She said that's a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It's like visiting a family grave.
Packed in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older graves from World War I and World War II and the Vietnam War as their goal, as these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children played and couples held hands while they carried the fresh pine branches to the greying tombstones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red loop attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost calm.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 wreaths to decorate this section, but the gloomy mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends stuck together in the icy air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black-and-white maps, which had been put into the damp mud for those whose tombstones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son's grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio to visit the burial site of Marine Infranterie sergeant David Shane Spicer, who fell in combat in July.
No one should ever forget why we're free... my son paid for it, she said.
"When I haven't been around for a long time, I want someone to remember him."
US government contractor arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a US government contractor who sold mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, said representatives of the State Department on Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc. based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for customers, such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officers from the U.S. Interest Group in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5th.
The specific charges have not yet been published, although according to Cuban law a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything, under the charge of "hazard".
All so-called counterrevolutionary activities, including light protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly requested permission to leave the country to receive prices, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to increase tensions between the Castro brother's communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a "slow" rapprochement to improve relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported by the New York Times on Friday night.
The new US policy places great importance on the United States to provide compensation if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought after products in a country where the average salary of a government employee is $15 a month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, they are used primarily for sending text messages, as a 15-minute telephone call would cost a daily wage.
Internet usage on the island is extremely restricted.
It is available in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government offices, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens who are in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes like drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokesperson for the U.S. Interest Representation in Havana.
Berbena said she couldn't give any more information about the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the delivery of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the "Human Rights Watch" group, who recently published a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, Same Cuba", an allusion to the appointment of Raul Castro as the country's leader, replacing the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that the defendants were very often arrested, sentenced and imprisoned within one day.
He said that probably any solution would be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just at the time when both countries are moving towards each other for more willingness to dialogue.
Pakistani government officials uncover plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities discovered on Saturday a supposedly leading head of a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill U.S. soldiers, and said that they hoped this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters searching the Internet for radicalized young men.
Investigators said that they had been looking for an opaque insurgent, known as Saifullah, who had invited the men to Pakistan after he had tracked them down because one of them had made positive comments on terrorist attacks on the YouTube Internet video page.
After their arrival in Pakistan, Saifullah became the leader of these men and tried to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan's tribal belt, which is home to Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of Pakistan's intelligence service who was briefed on the matter said on Saturday that Saifullah could not convince the Al Qaeda leaders that the men are not part of a CIA conspiracy to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were detained for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far away from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist refuge.
They were considered part of a covert operation.
Therefore, they were rejected, said the government official, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said that the men were by no means discouraged and kept trying to get the right recommendations to get access to the Al Qaeda camps when they were arrested by the Pakistani prison authorities.
The case of the five men - who continue to be in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI - underlines the crucial role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and, possibly more importantly, in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, U.S. intelligence has made it a matter of utmost urgency to place human assets within Al Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization act as porters who do not let in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American wannabe recruits are subject to a special audit by A Qaeda, analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to US targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered to be tremendously attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst at the NEFA Foundation based in the United States, said that terrorist groups have also become much more cautious in recent years regarding who they are allowing access, as the U.S. secret services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to get someone into these groups, what better way could you go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?, said Kohlmann.
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of demonstrators call for climate "action" in Copenhagen
Tens of thousands of demonstrators marched through the streets here on Saturday and demanded bolder action on climate protection from the negotiators in the city's Bella Congress Centre.
Demonstrators said that 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were more likely to amount to about 25,000.
The event was relatively peaceful, although a handful of masked activists lit small explosive devices near some government buildings in the city centre.
On one day, when little happened in the UN-sponsored climate negotiations, thousands of activists with banners wandered through the city, where "There is no Planet B" was written in English, and one in Spanish, which declared "The Earth says "Enough".
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, the photographer Helena Christensen, who said that her travels to Peru, her mother's country of birth, made her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country has to contend with due to the already noticeable effects of climate change.
That is part of the reasons why I decided to take part in the big demonstration - to pass the floor and appeal to the world leaders to bring about a fair, ambitious and binding agreement, she said.
It is not an easy task, but it must be done now and there is no way around it.
The police stopped the demonstrators from getting too close to the Bella Centre and said they had arrested 19 people, mainly due to the fact that they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited in demonstrations.
According to a spectator who didn't want to be named because he is involved in the climate negotiations, masked protesters in black clothes lit several explosive devices near the main canal in Copenhagen, near which several ministries are located.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they started as flares, but then followed by "a few big explosions."
Inside the convention center, people gathered in front of television screens to follow the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest apparently did not reach the awareness of the main officials, such as Su Wie, China's chief climate negotiator.
When asked if he thought that the demonstration had a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: "This is something I was not aware of."
He then continued in Mandarin and said, "Because the venue is big, I can't hear what's happening outside."
He noted that it depends on the individual's perspective whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the focus of the general public and various sectors on the topic of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they disturb the negotiations or the freedom of other people".
Test data show persistent race gap
The evidence of mathematics performance last week was welcome good news for public schools in Washington D.C.
Although Washington District is still far behind the country's high-performance schools, the evidence shows that the fourth and eighth graders have made faster progress over the past two years than cities including Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what is included in the latest National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) figures is the persistent performance gap between African American and white students, both at local and national level.
The average score of the white fourth graders from Washington D.C. rose from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) in the last two years, but that of their African American peers rose only three points from 209 to 212.
In reality, the performance gap rose from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the Afro-American eighth graders remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white pupils was not included in the test data as the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was captured in this district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score that children of both groups have achieved has increased over this period, the difference with now 58 points has hardly decreased.
Some of the district's educational supporters expressed concern last week that the results celebrated by school Chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic Mayor Adrian M. Fenty were largely driven by white students who are already powerful children anyway.
This suggests that we have raised the overall ranking by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, board member of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group that advocates educational equality in Washington D.C.
I am not jumping up and down for a span of two or three points, said Democratic Washington City Councilman Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee's management style, said the message of exam scores is that the city's middle schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, I respect that.
What frightens me, however, is that we do not spend nearly the time and energy we need to use for our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of low-performance students.
This autumn, for example, some teachers are being trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, aimed at students in the upper classes of primary and middle school, who have not mastered basic literacy skills at the beginning of their school career and who are significantly behind their peers of the same age.
Everyday mathematics, a curriculum that focuses on games and lifelike experiences from kindergarten to sixth grade, was brought to Washington under former senior school inspector Clifford Janey, and this curriculum is attributed to some of the NAEP progress reported last week.
I believe that we must continue to work to make the best of the measures available to students below grades, Rhee said.
Others say that the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the extra money and resources for the low-performance schools that are necessary to reduce the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, Professor of Education at the University of California in Berkeley, who is investigating urban exam results.
The conventional remedy is to focus its resources and management reforms on the schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C.
The objective could have political aftermaths working against this important item on the agenda.
The weak point is, of course, as with other urban school inspectors, that they are trying to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to ensure that we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighbourhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said this week in an interview that one of the most important elements for closing the performance gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with the charter schools.
One must increase the school year to nearly 200 days in order to have the power to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teachers' union last year over 185 days per year, which he regarded as "a milestone" on the way to a greater increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people than future prospects
The coach reaches the Gettysburg-College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, steps out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, the brick facades and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela's parents barely finished high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was rescued in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Their attitude and that of the other eighth graders of the group who explore Gettysburg, where the tuition costs 38,690 dollars per year, was more of an awe-inspiring visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes! I will be here soon!" cried Graciela, who would like to study medicine, when the leader announced that they had now entered the building for science.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when the low professor-to-student ratio of the school was reported to her.
The college in Pennsylvania was the 7th one the children visited on their three-day tour and now they have taken up the intended message completely: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of children born in the United States of Hispanic immigrants who do not finish high school or become pregnant as teenagers, on the other hand, there are hundreds of thousands who receive the college education needed to get into the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these "second generation" of Hispanic Americans completes college – which is a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the US without having completed high school.
Their success stories are important, say researchers, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country's workforce.
Those who study powerful children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive to success.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counselling programs also play a major role by helping Graciela and millions of children like her to get to college, especially if these efforts persist over a long period of time.
Looking at low-income children whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, a single measure will not solve the problem at any time, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California in Davis, who studied Hispanic American students.
We need to think about providing these children with a supportive network from preschool to high school.
The federal program that Graciela's college tour funded is a useful example.
It is known as GEAR UP - Turn up a gear - and provides more than $300 million a year for local school systems to launch college preparation programs that start when low-income students are in middle school and continue to run until they have completed high school.
According to the US Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, more than 60% of whom went to college.
Iraqi Oil Ministry signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to persuade major oil companies to rebuild its damaged infrastructure at two auctions concluded on Saturday.
The ten contracts concluded with foreign oil companies by the Iraqi Ministry of Oil suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are ready to play an important role in the renovation of the Iraqi oil industry, which has been paralysed for decades by war and economic sanctions.
American companies could only book shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields.
Seven American companies had paid to participate in the second auction, which started on Friday.
The only company that has made a bid has made a shortcoming.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The thinly sown representatives of American oil multinationals in opening up the Iraqi oil industry surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after six years of war, and instead of US companies, Asians and Europeans are giving way, said Ruba Husari, editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no further offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns, underlined by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday, and political instability from the withdrawal of the US military, have probably prevented American oil companies from doing so, analysts said they would engage more in Iraq, which has the world's third largest proven crude oil reserves.
US companies have been disadvantaged in some cases because competitors, especially the Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower wage costs and are more likely to take risks because they do not have to account for shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies that could enter into contracts with the Department.
Larger US companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, who have close ties with the Iraqi oil ministry and have supported them with technical advice in recent years, have run out.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The state-owned China National Petroleum Corporation has offered more contracts than any other company and was able to go home with large packages of contracts for two larger fields.
We all know, said the spokesman for the oil ministry, Assam Jihad, that China is on its way to becoming one of the greats of the world economy as well as a technology power.
We are convinced that the Chinese company can compete with its competitors and will fulfil its obligations to Iraq.
Companies preselected for bids were bids, which were then compared to the fee per barrel of oil the Ministry was willing to pay to increase the output of each field beyond the current level.
Top planner of Al Qaeda apparently killed in Pakistan
In an obvious U.S. missile attack along the Pakistani border with Afghanistan, a top Al Qaeda planner is said to have been killed this week, reported representatives of the U.S. counter-terrorism campaign on Friday.
This would be, if it were confirmed, the second fatal attack on a senior terrorist organization leader this autumn.
Saleh al-Somali was one of the two Arabs who, according to U.S. sources and Pakistani authorities, were said to have been killed by a number of rockets that hit their vehicle near the city of Miran Shah in the province of North Waziristan on Tuesday.
Local authorities reported that the rockets were fired by a type of drone used by the CIA in Pakistan's lawless tribal belt.
They were driving in a white vehicle towards the Afghan border when the car was hit, a government representative of a Pakistani civilian intelligence agency from Miran Shah said by phone.
Locals suspected of belonging to the militants ran to the site and quickly took everything that was left of the "completely destroyed bodies".
The local authorities were unable to confirm the identity of the victims, but two representatives of the US counter-terrorism movement cited indefinite evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as the leading Al-Qaeda military planner who led operations of terrorist groups outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
He was involved in conspiracies around the world, noted a senior official who wanted to remain anonymous and pointed to the delicate nature of US air strikes on Pakistani soil.
If one assumes its central role as given, this also included planning attacks against the US and Europe.
He took strategic instructions from the top leaders of Al Qaeda and turned them into operational planning for possible terrorist attacks.
The second American official said that Somali had quickly ascended to the Al Qaeda hierarchy and maintained the best ties with other extremist groups in the region.
He may not be known to some Americans, said the second official, but this does not in any way reduce the danger he posed to us and our allies.
If his death were confirmed, Somali would be the second leading Al-Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal area, and three other top activists.
The rate of attacks by CIA drones has decreased from an average of six operations per month to two since the summer, according to a summary of the Long War Journal, a website run by a non-profit organization.
The decline may be based on improved tactics by terrorist groups that have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while brutally killing suspected informants, the site reported.
Leading UN envoy in Kabul will resign
The UN's leading envoy in Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday that he would resign from office in March, ending a stormy term of office clouded by allegations of widespread corruption in the UN-backed Afghan presidential election.
Eide's departure took place when the Obama administration decided to send another 30,000 US soldiers to Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said that he supported the increase in troops, but he also expressed his concern that the US military withdrawal schedule, which is to begin in 18 months, could cause other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to speed up the construction of Afghan security forces, sending the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul.
The commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian helpers to help with the political transition of Afghanistan.
The increase on the military side must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said that he did not resign from office, but only fulfilled an agreement made in March 2008 with his family to remain in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted the notification to UN
Secretary General Ban Ki-moon now forward so that he has time to provide a replacement.
What I said was that he'd better start looking for a successor, said Eide.
When I came here, there was a two-month vacuum between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
Ban has started searching for a replacement according to UN representatives.
The UN representatives say that he has considered the Swedish-Italian-born Staffan di Mistura, who recently led the UN mission in Baghdad and the Frenchman Jean-Marie Guéhenno, who previously led UN peace operations.
Eide's position in Afghanistan was put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused him in September of favoring President Hamid Karzai in the country's presidential election and covering up evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eides has rejected all accusations, but he also said that Galbraith's accusations - who was fired - "have undoubtedly harmed the mission because there has already been a great deal of scepticism about international interference in the election."
Eide said that he recommended the appointment of a leading civilian representative to coordinate the relief efforts of the American-led forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged that the UN leadership allow his successor to hire more personnel from the United States and other Western countries to donate to the Afghan mission, and said that this would strengthen their confidence in the proper use of their money.
Eide expressed his disappointment at restricting his forces in Afghanistan and said that the cumbersome UN recruitment arrangements have undermined his ability to bring in capable people.
The UN rules are designed in such a way that since May, he said, I could only hire one person.
This is disastrous and must not go on like this.
US Secretary of Defense Gates: Iran must expect additional sanctions
Defense Minister Robert M. Gates said Friday that the world powers will soon impose "significant additional sanctions" on Iran because he did not participate in talks about his nuclear plans.
During a seven-day journey through the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, Gates spoke to a group of approximately 300 US soldiers in northern Iraq and played down the prospect of a military action against the Islamic Republic of Iran.
In Iran, there are no good choices, he said in answer to a soldier's question about the likelihood of such a development.
"One of the things that are on my mind is, if we have learned something from Iraq over the past six years, the war's own unpredictability."
The Obama administration is considering a package of sanctions aimed at the military and political elite of Iran, but Gates has announced that some sanctions could also affect the average Iranian.
He said that a "package of positive and negative incentives" is needed "to convince the Iranian government that it is actually less protected by nuclear weapons" because "their people will suffer tremendously" from the sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement by the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the American government joined the European leaders in warning that Iran will have to face "credible" consequences if it does not comply with the demands of the UN Security Council and its nuclear monitoring organisation, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran continues to claim that the knowledge of nuclear technology should only be gained for peaceful purposes.
During talks in Geneva on 1 October, Iran said that it would resume talks to limit its nuclear programme and would forego a substantial part of its stock of enriched uranium in exchange for much-needed nuclear fuel for its medical research reactor.
The US government has pushed for this kind of agreement to build trust between the two parties and gain time for negotiations.
But Iran seems to have left the negotiations on the provisional agreements since then -- in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership disagrees on whether they should commit themselves to the United States.
Gates said that Iran has simply left the international community behind in relation to some of the proposals they had already agreed to at the beginning of October, openly saying that the international community, including the Russians and Chinese, has brought them together in a way that they have never been in connection with important additional sanctions for Iran.
President Obama has set the 31 Dec as the deadline for Iran to respond to these proposals before pursuing other options, including those that Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called "impressive sanctions."
In a statement issued in New York, Iran's representation at the United Nations condemned what it called "fundamental and unfundamental claims" by some Security Council members on Iran's nuclear activities on Thursday, saying that they are ready to continue the talks with the United States and five other world powers "to achieve an appropriate long-term solution."
Gates, who was to return to Washington last Friday, met Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki in the morning before he flew to the oil-rich Kurdish region in Iraq to meet the soldiers in Kirkuk and with Kurdish officials in Irbil.
The tensions between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq remain high, especially in terms of borders, property rights and the distribution of public revenue.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the conflict potential to prevent delays in US plans to reduce American troop strength from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also tried to dispel Kurdish concern about the imminent withdrawal of troops. US representatives quoted Gates, who said to Masud Barzani, President of the Kurdish regional government, "We will receive your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within a unified Iraq.
We will not leave you."
A Change of Course in Ageing China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters giving them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One baby more means a grave more."
They learned these lessons so well that, when government officials in Shanghai, who were suddenly starting to change the course and encourage young couples to have more than one child, due to the low birth rate and the ageing population this summer, their answer was immediate and definitive: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a head of personnel with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously fat, spoiled single children, who are affectionately called "little emperors", a population crisis in the country is looming.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN
Department of Population Issues, while the number of population groups aged 60 and over in 2020 is set to increase from 16.7 percent of the population to 31.1 percent by 2050. This is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and olders accounted for almost 22 percent of reported Shanghai residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, said that couples of childbearing age must have babies to "help reduce the ratio of ageing populations and alleviate the labour shortage of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A Gradual Relaxation
Established in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Married couples who violate this policy have to face enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical demands of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of politics.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had gender-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child politics.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University's Department of Population Research, said that government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with whom a partner is an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters instructing families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines describing in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and put leaflets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice to those who have more than one child.
The response was not very encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said that an upswing can be seen in the requests of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
For the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Family Planning Committee of Caolu Township in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people no longer want to have children.
