The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it wouldn't be anything special.
However, Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, reporting Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the magazine Science of Thursday.
About 215 million years ago, the animal lived in today's New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they collected the remains of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primal dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three most important developmental lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "long necks" and their relatives, and the plants-eating Ornithischia (bird basin dinosaurs), which included the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus, for example.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is an original Theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags, such as the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the earth, which at that time formed a single landmass as a supercontinent Pangäa.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa Hallae, found the remains of two other, not very closely related Theropods speaks for this.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could result in a distorted picture, because in South America many primitive dinosaur fossils have simply been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile trunk to the dominant land vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still puzzling.
During the Triassic the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flight dinosaurs and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relatives died out on the border from the Triassic to the Jura.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact caused a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic and since then a shadow existence: the mammals.
