Dream worlds
Some see images in awake state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred not only in the mentally ill and in the drug rush.
As long as it happens in sleep, it's all right.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can indulge ourselves uninhibited in the wildest imaginations and imaginations.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in growth, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicts in the modern Western world, at least as a stranger.
But such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in the drug rush.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion, and reality blur.
Dream-like altered waking states can occur in various forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of rapture, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neuronal messenger substances of the brain - especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different brain parts is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during a schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no more power over it
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all inconsistencies, delusions, illusions of such a kind".
It is autumn 2001 when Henning T. turns into a comic figure.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky.
Gravity has no more power over him, it floats on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted frets, squeezing.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and radio.
He can't stand them anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a loop and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a loudspeaker and lays the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The noose is loosening.
This is supposed to be a lesson for you, the voices screaming in a drum-skin-scrapping choir, "go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last is 2 years old, the first is almost 20 years old.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, moreover he is manic-depressive, he takes medications against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric hospitals it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, those affected can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, megalomania, relationship or persecution.
Voice listening is particularly common - voices that command, comment or dialogize.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to separate important things from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a flood of ideas and fantasies that stem from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of the event, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is overwhelmed by the events, just like in a dream, and he cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenic patients therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
They are not usually able to compare reality, the illusions are cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in life
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience takes place within the real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers still pose puzzles.
Exceptions can cause any human being to lose his or her reference to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that minimal brain damage is present in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development by a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, for example, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which, moreover, does not manifest itself for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also cause psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains run hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a question of viewpoint.
For ten years, Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are one of the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of astonishingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brain of healthy people is hallucinated under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, says the box, are composed of memory contents that are normally held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is missing.
Drugs can cause this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also excitement, stress, heartbreak or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents said that they had experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the Gymnasium there.
A normal girl, actually.
If there weren't the pictures and voices.
During the break it can happen that a shabby boy with long, dark hair speaks to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
She's awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher is presenting a new student in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations for all the others, both audible and visible on the table.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and much too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees are the faces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her about it, they think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed her Abitur last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of despair
When a person is socially isolated or suffers from disincentives, he is most likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I guess the brain is then underworked and provides its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she found out at 13 that the man she calls Papa has not been her biological father since she could think.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations have the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, such as Sarah K., to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is taking place in the brain, the reality is there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they work so real."
Even nightly dream images evaluate caste as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
In contrast to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their illusions as unreal.
Therefore, Kasten advises his patients to value hallucinations as a special ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our overly mind-centered world, imaginary experiences are mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative delusion - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-like altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state in hindsight.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with loss of self and world, for example, by persistent, total inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a change of world takes place, but the real situation is visualized in imagination.
An intense form of sense and meaning in a situation that is in itself unbearable, which enables us humans to create our own ability not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body in the intensive care unit is doomed to motionlessness.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce drugs from blood.
Swallowed by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, his hospital bed surfs in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He goes up completely in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is another state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travels are still overly clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug rush show how fragile our inner images of external reality are in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist caste, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
