75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fruitability and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market as limited due to their maternity.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to set up a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not, and if so, what kind of occupation they perform.
Those of them who do no other work outside the house, work only half-day or have no fixed employment contract, become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with fixed employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a fixed job only receive their first child on average 3.7 years after moving together, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with a fixed job, who have taken longer to achieve this and who have only realized their moving together and the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, although less than the calendar regarding the readiness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women when marrying and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only have a primary or higher education, were first mother on average with 25,1 or 32,1 respectively.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a primary degree are already getting married and having their first child before their first permanent employment, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly the other way around and first look for a permanent employment and get married after it and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
